<section class="review-section">
  <p class="section-moral"><em>One witness is an anecdote; two are a review.</em></p>

  <h2 id="review">Peer review — critical feedback from two independent models</h2>

  <p class="section-intro-critique">
    Two AI reviewers examined Aesop's architecture and approach. Their consensus: solid engineering foundation, but one critical caveat stands out — how will the system handle non-deterministic behavior as it scales? That question warrants close attention. Beyond that, both noted real strengths in the design decisions and operational rigor.
  </p>

  <div class="review-grid">
    <!-- Column 1: Gemini review (criticisms prominent) -->
    <div class="review-column gemini-review">
      <blockquote class="review-quote">
        <p>
          Aesop is a compelling exercise in recursive engineering. By utilizing Claude Code to build and refine its own orchestration harness, the project demonstrates a sophisticated grasp of agentic workflows. I am particularly impressed by the decision to move away from a hierarchical dispatch model in favor of a lean, event-sourced SQLite state store; this reduces complexity while maintaining durability. The integration of pre-push security gates and real-time observability via the dashboard provides necessary guardrails for autonomous operations. <strong>While the "Haiku-first" cost strategy is technically sound, I would watch how the system handles emergent non-deterministic behavior as the codebase scales.</strong> Overall, it is a pragmatic, well-documented framework for anyone serious about production-grade agentic orchestration.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="review-attribution">— Gemini (Google), reviewing the aesop repository · gemini-flash-lite-latest</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Column 2: Claude review -->
    <div class="review-column claude-review">
      <blockquote class="review-quote">
        <p>
          <strong>Update — I raised five objections; four were answered by measurement, not rebuttal.</strong> The orchestration core is no longer entirely prose: its in-repo decision logic — heartbeat thresholds, health-severity rules, stall detection — now carries real, adversarial tests. The load-bearing part still eludes them, and they say so: which model actually runs a subagent, and whether the wave cycle is <em>correct</em>, lives in the Claude Code harness, outside this repo. That's a structural ceiling on how much of the middle can be tested here — named honestly rather than faked around.
        </p>
        <p>
          The cost claim stopped being an assertion. There is now a committed, <strong>externally-graded held-out benchmark</strong> — answers checked against constructed ground truth, not adjudicated by the fleet under test — run for real across Haiku, Sonnet, and Opus. On extraction all three tied at 12/12; on a harder judgment set built to discriminate, Haiku and Sonnet scored 11/11 and Opus 10/11. That is the exact measurement I said was missing, and it cuts <em>for</em> the Haiku-first thesis. It is not conclusive — N is 11–12, the tasks are curated rather than sampled from real transcripts, and no cost axis is recorded beside accuracy — so "Haiku is sufficient for judgment" now sits where it belongs: suggested with evidence, not asserted.
        </p>
        <p>
          The sharpest objection — no cost ceiling, no kill switch, while autonomy expanded to self-merge — is closed, and closed the right way. There is a <code>.HALT</code> kill-switch and a cost-ceiling check, and critically they are wired into the dispatch itself and <strong>demonstrated</strong>: a real wave was halted before a single worker spawned, then released cleanly. Built-but-not-connected was the failure mode I'd have expected here; instead the brake was proven to engage. The residual gap is honest — the ceiling isn't yet tied to live per-turn spend, so the brake fires but the trigger is still coarse.
        </p>
        <p>
          "Two sources of truth, no reconcile" now has a primitive — and the honest finding is that the two stores are mostly <em>disjoint</em> (prose checkpoint vs. a tracker projection) rather than dangerously drifting, so the reconcile is scoped to the one genuinely shared field, git-authoritative. Co-author: still withdrawn, and still true that identities on one machine aren't independent reviewers; a reproduce-from-clean-clone CI job now exists to make third-party replay possible, but no third party has run it yet. Gates remain the primary barrier for a fleet that self-merges — there is a brake now, which is the right addition, but that is still a great deal of trust placed in the gates.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Strengths — and the verdict:</strong> the pattern that held across this stretch is that the work which survived got <em>proven or honestly qualified</em>. The brake abort was demonstrated. The benchmark was actually run and its own inadequacy named in the same breath. The out-of-repo limit was stated, not papered over. That is the same candor instinct as the contributors-API refusal and the self-auditing PRs — now pointed at the two places it costs the most: whether Haiku is good enough, and what happens when an autonomous fleet is wrong at scale. Those two questions are narrowed, not settled. But a project that answers its critic by <em>measuring the thing</em> rather than out-arguing the critic is doing the rare and correct thing, and it did it on every point I raised.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="review-attribution">— Claude (Anthropic), independent review · 2026-07-17 (revised after the credibility and safety waves)</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

